According to a Wall Street Journal article by Arlene Weintraub, couples who put their marriage first report higher fulfillment than those that do not. It’s important to recognize that simply working together is not enough. Every marriage is fulfilling when both parties are participating.

Recognizing this, Dr. John Gottman and his colleagues at the Gottman Institute follow couples through the First Five Years of Marriage, a time which is typically when spouses are still head over heels in love. The Gottman Institute’s goal is to teach the skills needed for a healthy long term marriage.

Source: thegottmaninstitute.com

What couples tend to miss is the end goal of their relationship. The time after the honeymoon is when couples really have to talk about their marital goals. According to Weintraub, couples should ask themselves:

What do we want out of the relationship?

Do we have the same goals?

Will these goals change in the next five to ten years?

Do we need to change to fit these goals?

The Gottman Institute uses the following scenario to help couples plan for their future.
